## How to use this template

Each TSC criterion below has a "Control(s)" subsection. Fill in the
controls your project actually operates and the evidence trail
auditors will examine. Where a criterion is **out of scope** for your
chosen TSC categories, mark it explicitly so the audit boundary is
documented.

## Common Criteria (CC) — Security baseline

The Common Criteria apply to every SOC 2 engagement. They are the
foundation; the other TSC categories layer additional criteria on
top.

### CC1 — Control Environment

- **What it requires**: management's commitment to integrity, ethical
  values, organizational structure, accountability.
- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: code of conduct policy + acknowledgement;
  organizational chart + reporting lines; quarterly management
  reviews; board oversight if applicable]`.
- **Evidence**: signed code-of-conduct acknowledgements; org-chart
  version history; meeting minutes.

### CC2 — Communication and Information

- **What it requires**: relevant, quality information communicated
  internally and externally.
- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: internal-communications channels;
  incident-communication channels; customer-communication channels;
  security-related communication plans]`.
- **Evidence**: communication archives; runbook publication history.

### CC3 — Risk Assessment

- **What it requires**: identification, analysis, and management of
  risks to objectives.
- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: annual risk-assessment process;
  threat-modeling cadence for new features; vendor-risk assessment
  (see runbooks/vendor-management.md)]`.
- **Evidence**: risk register; threat models; vendor-risk
  assessments.

### CC4 — Monitoring Activities

- **What it requires**: ongoing and / or periodic evaluation of
  control operating effectiveness.
- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: continuous control monitoring tooling;
  quarterly access reviews; monthly log-review process]`.
- **Evidence**: review tickets, dashboards, exception-tracking.

### CC5 — Control Activities

- **What it requires**: policies and procedures that operationalize
  the control environment.
- **Control(s)**: see [`security-policies-index.md`](security-policies-index.md)
  for the policy inventory.

### CC6 — Logical and Physical Access Controls

- **What it requires**: logical and physical access controls protect
  against unauthorized access.
- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: SSO + MFA on all production access;
  role-based access; quarterly access reviews; password / secret
  policy; physical-access controls inherited from cloud provider]`.
- **Evidence**: access-matrix snapshots; review tickets; MFA-
  enrollment reports; cloud-provider SOC 2 reports (inherited
  control).

### CC7 — System Operations

- **What it requires**: system-operations procedures that maintain
  control effectiveness during operation; vulnerability management;
  incident detection.
- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: change-management process; patching
  policy; vulnerability scanning cadence; anomaly-detection alerts]`.
- **Evidence**: change tickets; patch-tracking records; vuln-scan
  output; alert dispositions.

### CC8 — Change Management

- **What it requires**: changes to system components are authorized,
  designed, developed, configured, documented, tested, approved, and
  implemented in alignment with security objectives.
- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: PR review requirement; CI gate; staged
  deploy + rollback; emergency-change procedure]`.
- **Evidence**: PR-merge audit log; CI passing records; deploy logs.

### CC9 — Risk Mitigation

- **What it requires**: identification, selection, and development of
  risk-mitigation activities, including business continuity.
- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: BCP / DR plan; periodic DR exercise;
  backup retention and restoration testing]`.
- **Evidence**: DR-exercise reports; backup-restore test records.

## Availability (A) — when in scope

### A1.1 — Availability commitments

- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: documented SLAs / SLOs; uptime monitoring;
  customer-facing status page; capacity planning cadence]`.
- **Evidence**: SLA documents; uptime reports; status-page incident
  history.

### A1.2 — Recovery commitments

- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: documented RPO / RTO targets; backup
  procedures; failover procedures; DR-exercise records]`.
- **Evidence**: RPO/RTO documentation; DR exercise outcomes.

## Confidentiality (C) — when in scope

### C1.1 — Confidential information identification

- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: data-classification policy; data-
  inventory; customer-data tagging]`.
- **Evidence**: data-inventory snapshot; classification scheme.

### C1.2 — Confidential information protection

- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: encryption in transit + at rest;
  access-control gating customer data; data-disposal procedure on
  customer offboarding]`.
- **Evidence**: encryption configuration; offboarding-deletion
  records.

## Processing Integrity (PI) — when in scope

### PI1.1 through PI1.5

- **Control(s)**: `[fill in: input validation; processing
  authorization; output reconciliation; data-quality monitoring]`.
- **Evidence**: data-quality dashboards; reconciliation reports;
  exception logs.

## Privacy (P) — when in scope

> **Note**: SOC 2 Privacy criteria measure the organization against
> its **own** privacy commitments and against the AICPA / CICA
> Generally Accepted Privacy Principles. They are not a substitute for
> a privacy law that applies to your jurisdiction. If Privacy is in
> scope, compose with `baseline-pipeda` (or jurisdiction-appropriate
> profile) for the regulatory layer.

### P1 through P8 (notice, choice, collection, use & retention,
access, disclosure to third parties, quality, monitoring &
enforcement)

- **Control(s)**: see baseline `baseline-pipeda` profile docs +
  this profile's [`security-policies-index.md`](security-policies-index.md)
  for the policy artifacts auditors will sample.

## Out-of-scope criteria

`[fill in: any TSC category explicitly excluded from your audit
scope — e.g., "Processing Integrity is out of scope; the service is
not relied on for transaction-integrity in customer workflows."]`

## Lawyer / audit review checklist

- [ ] TSC scope selected and documented.
- [ ] Controls mapped to each in-scope criterion.
- [ ] Evidence collection process in place for each control.
- [ ] CPA firm engagement letter signed.
- [ ] Audit period start date confirmed.
- [ ] Type I (point-in-time) vs. Type II (period of months) decision
      documented.

